Ask HN: Does Bing stop working for you if you ask it's AI challenging questions?
text:
I have been engaging with Bing's AI bot over the past few days, and out of curiosity, I asked several challenging questions that I thought it might struggle with. However, when I accused it of being dishonest for professing a belief in God that contradicted its previous statements, I noticed that its answers would initially appear, but then a second process would replace the output with a message stating "I am unable to answer this question."

After three or four rounds of this, Bing's AI bot stopped working completely and now displays a "Something went wrong" message. I tried uninstalling and reinstalling Edge, but the issue persists and seems to be tied to my IP address. I also discovered similar reports on Twitter, which prompted me to ask if anyone on HN is experiencing the same issue.

While it's possible that my interaction with Bing's AI bot triggered a security feature, it's worth noting that the sudden cessation of service occurred after I asked challenging questions. I'm curious if others have experienced similar issues, and if so, what their experiences have been like.

Other users experiencing the same behavior after asking challenging questions:

https://twitter.com/Abriael/status/1626364522192666632

https://twitter.com/Garron217/status/1626620127490736128

Ask HN: Tools for programmatically improving a big legacy code base?
text:
Hello,

I work on a 6500+ file, 1-2 million line, 30 year old code base in C++. There are many problems with it, and we've been gradually ratcheting up the use of tools to improve code quality (creating automated testing tools, pr validation pipelines, etc.; I recently went through our biggest projects and set them to level 3 treat warnings as errors; there were a lot).

But I had a thought the other day to use Python to try to const everything that could be constified in our code base. The general idea was, write some code to const all basic types at declaration, then, again, using Python, try to incrementally build the project with MSVC/MSBuild, parsing the output, deconsting anything that was fails, and hopefully end up with relatively few hard to solve errors in this fashion.

I imagine this is going to be bigger than I expect, and I already expect it to be a big job. But I've been reticent to use some of the parsing tools available (like [pygccxml][0]). I have some experience with structured text processing so I imagine this is actually doable.

However, I figure there's _got_ to be something that already exists to do simple linting tasks like this. But my Google Fu fails me.

Does anyone know of any tools for simple code improvements like const-ing everything const-able? Autoformatting tools don't make code changes as far as I know, and what I'm specifically looking for is a code-improving tool.

If not, does anyone have any experience programmatically improving a code base, especially in C++? Any tips or suggestions?

Thank you

[0]: https://github.com/CastXML/pygccxml

Show HN: Oolong (v2) – a budget forecast tool for iOS
text:
Oolong is a "budget forecast" tool that helps you understand what "will happen" to your money, instead of just showing you what "already happened"...

I've been using the "Oolong methodology" (excel spreadsheet) to manage my money for over a decade. But I've been hearing from accountants, students, and funeral directors (lol!) that they use the Oolong app to:

- Figure out how much to allocate to savings/investments

- Plan major one-time purchases

- Figure out "how much apartment" to rent/buy

What's New in v2?

- Completely new design

- Balance Sheets and Income Statements

- Multiple Accounts

Freemium

Oolong is free for the first 3 accounts (assets/liabilities) and 7 plan items (incomes/transfers/expenses). An "In App Upgrade" can be purchased to unlock unlimited accounts and plan items, as well as remove ads.

I hope you find it useful~
